INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1508_L007$$, 2026, $$The Air Expendable Countermeasures (AECM) line provides funding for procurement of countermeasure self-protection devices for all United States Navy (USN) and United States Marine Corps (USMC) tactical,
 rotary and other fixed-wing aircraft. AECM supports fleet aircrew training, readiness and operational combat requirements for all USN and USMC aircraft. Delivering airborne defensive Electronic Warfare (EW)
 self-protection solutions enables the global warfighter success against an evolving adversary. In FY2022, the AECM program began Common Carriage (CC) procurements to standardize countermeasures
 across all Services and increase operability across multiple platforms. The CC solution (square form factor) permits aircraft to carry additional, more advanced countermeasures resulting in increased readiness/
 capability/lethality/survivability against current and emerging threat systems. CC will utilize Research, Development, Test & Evaluation, Navy, (RDT&E,N) Program Element 0604270N, Project Unit 3309 and
 Aircraft Procurement, Navy, Modification, Program Element: 0204161N, Operational Safety Improvement Program 006-00. The AECM Program is divided into the following threat related groupings: (1) Active
 Jammers (2) Infrared (IR) Decoys (3) associated Impulse Cartridges (4) Chaff Countermeasures and (5) F-35 Countermeasures.

 ACTIVE JAMMERS: Dual Band Decoy (DBD) is a future active jammer which began with a Demonstration of Existing Technologies contract that awarded in FY2019 and an Engineering, Manufacturing
 Development (EMD) contract that awarded in FY2023. DBD will replace the current active jammer Fiber Optic Towed Decoy (FOTD) and significantly improve F/A-18E/F survivability against emerging radar-
 guided threats. The FOTD, when integrated with the rest of the F/A-18E/F EW suite (i.e., ALQ-214, ALR-67(V)3, ALE-47) and with the associated cockpit controls, displays and other avionics, significantly
 improves the survivability of the host aircraft in a Radio Frequency (RF) threat environment. Integrated Defensive Electronic Countermeasure Radio Frequency Countermeasure (RFCM) has transitioned to Block
 4 which utilizes FOTD integrated hardware to include Electronic Frequency Converter (EFC) and Integrated Multi-Purpose Launch Controller (IMPLC). DBD will utilize RDT&E,N, Program Element 0604270N,
 Project Unit 2175. DBD production replaces the FOTD in FY2025. ALQ-260 Active Expendable Device (AED) is a self-contained, free fall active RFCM decoy providing enhanced multi-platform self-protection
 capability against Surface-to-Air Missiles (SAM) and Air-to-Air Missiles (AAM) threats. ALQ-260 provides aircrew with tailored solutions in a dense RF engagement environment and replaces the Gen-X legacy
 free fall active RFCM with modern hardware and techniques for enhanced capability. Development of an AED began with US Army DoD Ordnance Technology Consortium. Further development continued in
 FY2024 using RDT&E,N, Program Element 0604270N, Project Unit 3309. ALQ-260 is used on F-35B/C aircraft and will be used on F/A-18E/F. Procurements of ALQ-260 began in FY2025 to satisfy urgent F-35
 fleet requirements in response to a newly fielded RF missile guided threat system.

 IR DECOYS: The MJU-32/38/49 are currently used by all aircraft, except the KC130J/T, UC-35D and F-35B/C, to provide self-protection from SAM and AAM IR missiles. The MJU-61/64 are used on the
 KC-130J/T, UC-35D and F-35B/C aircraft to provide self-protection from SAM and AAM IR missiles. The SM875 is a dedicated, low cost training device. The MJU-57 provides a kinematic IR countermeasure
 to defeat specific Man-Portable Air Defense Systems (MANPADS) used on the F/A-18, MV-22, P-8, UC-12W and KC-130J. The MJU-66 is an advanced spectral countermeasure in support of KC-130J/T and
 UC-35D. The MJU-67 Multi-spectral flare provides an enhanced spectral signature required for USN/USMC aircraft self-protection against accelerated proliferation of advanced MANPADS. The procurement mix$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                    Date: April 2026
