INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1507_L008$$, 2026, $$The SM-6 BLK I/IA/IAU provides an extended range engagement capability to provide the air superiority and the umbrella of protection for joint U.S. forces and allies against the full spectrum of manned-fixed and
 rotary-winged aircraft, unmanned aerial vehicles, and land attack and anti-ship cruise missiles in flight. This capability contributes significantly to the continuous protection of forward deployed ground maneuver
 forces as well as theater assets. The SM-6 is the primary extended range air defense weapon for AEGIS cruisers and destroyers, Constellation class frigate and potentially future combatants.

 SM-6 BLK IA reflects a funding profile for a base plus two options that began in FY 2024 and completes in FY 2026. Advance Procurement information for this program is provided in exhibit 2234C.

 The SM-6 profile enables ramped production quantities defined by the Munitions Acceleration Council (MAC) via a Multi-Year Procurement (MYP) contract that begins in FY 2026 and completes in FY 2030.
 The MYP was authorized in Section 8010 (c) of the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2026. The MYP strategy for STANDARD Missile expands the capacity of the All-Up-Round (AUR) production line to 500
 AURs per year without additional government investment in capacity by leveraging savings to the contractor generated through economic order quantities of material from sub-vendors, enabled by the consistent
 demand laid forth in the MYP.

 Investments for increased production start-up began in FY 2022, for procuring additional special tooling and test equipment, to support increasing SM-6 BLK IAU production capacity to deliver 200 per year by FY
 2028.

 The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Standard Missile includes $362,375 thousand of discretionary and $1,048,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $1,410,375 thousand.
 - FY 2026 Discretionary: Based on the contract, the program will procure 55 SM-6 BLK IAs.
 - FY 2026 Mandatory (Reconciliation) supports $630,000 thousand to procure 114 SM-6 BLK IAs, $93,000 thousand for replacement of Navy long-range air and missile defense interceptors, $100,000 thousand
 for development of a second solid rocket motor source for Navy air defense, and $225,000 thousand for expansion of production capacity for Navy air defense and anti-ship missiles.

 The FY 2027 request for Standard missile includes $733,159 thousand of discretionary and $3,599,221 thousand of mandatory for a total of $4,332,380 thousand. The mandatory and discretionary funds are
 necessary to fully fund contract requirements for 239 SM-6 BLK IAs at a unit cost of $5,500 thousand and 301 SM-6 BLK IAUs at a unit cost of $7,841 thousand; 540 SM-6 Block IA/IAU (Mk 21 Mod 4) canisters
 at a unit cost of $402 thousand; production engineering support at a total cost of $30,689 thousand; SM-6 BLK IA/IAU Diminishing Manufacturing Sources (DMS) at a total cost of $24,870 thousand; SM-6 BLK
