INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1506_L023$$, 2026, $$The KC-130J aircraft is an all metal, high-wing, long-range, land-based monoplane. It is designed for cargo, tanker and troop carrier operations. For tanker operations, the aircrew will consist of a pilot, co-
 pilot, augmented crew member and two air refueling observers. Features include wing mounted refueling pods, an internal cargo ramp and door, crew and cargo compartment pressurization, ground and in-
 flight refueling, thermal deicing systems, and a Heads-Up Display (HUD). It is designed to take off and land on unimproved runways. The KC-130J aircraft is powered by four Allison AE 2100D3 Turbo-Prop
 Engines with four six-bladed composite propellers. The cockpit includes state-of-the-art electronics with Liquid Crystal Display (LCD) instrumentation. The improved power performance of the KC-130J provides
 40 percent greater range, 25 percent higher cruise ceiling, 46 percent decrease in time-to-climb, 21 percent increase in maximum speed and 41 percent decrease in maximum effort take-off run over the existing
 KC-130F/R/T models.

 The mission of the KC-130J is to provide tactical in-flight refueling and assault support transport. As a tactical transport, it is capable of conventional or aerial delivery of personnel or cargo. The aircraft is
 capable of carrying 92 combat troops or 64 paratroopers with equipment or 64 litters when configured as an ambulance. The aircraft is equipped for in-flight refueling to service two aircraft simultaneously and
 has a removable 3,600 gallon (13,627 liter) fuel tank in the cargo compartment. The KC-130J has the capability to refuel low-speed helicopters, tilt-rotor aircraft and high-speed jet aircraft. Aerial refueling of
 helicopters is normally conducted at 6,000 feet or below, at an airspeed of 115 KTS TAS and requires a ground change of the refueling basket. In response to the 2018 National Defense Strategy, the Marine
 Corps has refocused on potential threats in the Indo-Pacific region as an integral partner of the nation's naval expeditionary force and is implementing the Force Design plan. Included in that plan is the increase
 in VMGR capacity and the activation of a new KC-130J squadron at MCB Hawaii from FY2023-FY2026.

 The additional FY 2027 USNR aircraft, support equipment and training system procurements begin the C/KC-130T recapitalization towards the Program Of Record requirement and reestablishment of USNR
 aerial refueling capability to provide organic air-to-air and air delivered ground refueling in support of the Carrier Air Wing and Distributed Maritime Operations.

 The FY 2027 request for KC-130J includes $1,601,906 thousand of discretionary funding and $1,190,000 thousand of mandatory funding for a total of $2,791,906 thousand. FY 2027 total funding supports the
 procurement of nine (9) USMC KC-130J aircraft and nine (9) USNR (two (2) discretionary; seven (7) mandatory) KC-130J aircraft.

 FY 2026 spend plan amount for KC-130J includes $518,017 thousand of discretionary funding and $145,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) funding for a total of $663,017 thousand. FY 2026 total funding
 supports the procurement of five (5) USNR (four (4) congressional add; one (1) mandatory) KC-130J aircraft.

 Initial spares Prior Year total = $366.424M; Initial spares TC = $146.560M; Total Initial Spares = $946.647M$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                          Date: April 2026
