INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1506_L043$$, 2027, $$This line item funds the Common Operational Safety Improvement Programs (OSIPs), which enhance Electronic Countermeasures (ECM) equipment for strike and assault aircraft. The primary objective of the
 modification budget is to deliver advanced capabilities, including reprogrammable radar and missile warning systems, missile threat identification, sector direction finding, laser detection, and self-protection
 devices for applicable aircraft. Additionally, it supports the integration of hardware and software solutions that connect onboard Integrated Aircraft Survivability Equipment (iASE) with mission planning systems,
 ensuring seamless compatibility and improved operational effectiveness.

 (OSIP 014-90) AN/APR-39 Radar Warning Receiver (RWR):
 The AN/APR-39 Radar Signal Detecting Set (RSDS) is designed for United States Marine Corps (USMC), United States Navy (USN), United States Air Force (USAF), and United States Army (US Army) assault
 support aircraft. It provides onboard situational awareness and warnings of radar frequency (RF) threats. This budget supports the integration, validation/verification, Engineering Change Proposals (ECPs), and
 procurement of the upgraded APR-39 system.

 (OSIP 006-00) ALE-39 to ALE-47 Retrofit/Common Carriage (CC):
 Funding for this program addresses critical safety issues and significantly enhances aircraft survivability. The Common Carriage (CC) program focuses on improving the operational effectiveness of expendable
 countermeasures across the Department of War (DoW) and Joint Partners. Key benefits include increased expendable capacity, extended mission time-on-target, and reduced logistical footprint to support
 operations in contested environments. The Active Expendable Device (AED) Dispenser Assembly enables ALQ-260 integration, offering both detection and threat defeat capabilities in defensive Electronic
 Warfare (EW).
 This OSIP also supports the F/A-18E/F and EA-18G CC Multi-Layered Obstructed Brokered Hub (MOB Hub) and Integrated Aircraft Survivability Equipment (iASE) program. MOB Hub/iASE enhances tactical
 employment capabilities, improves situational awareness, and incorporates onboard and off-board data for iASE software application development.

 (OSIP 005-08) Direct Infrared Countermeasure (DIRCM)/Department of Navy Large Aircraft Infrared Countermeasure (DoN LAIRCM) AN/AAQ-24:
 The AN/AAQ-24 DoN LAIRCM System (B-Kit) configurations include one (1) LSPR-4000 Processor (replacing the DLPU nomenclature), two (2) Guardian Laser Tracker Assemblies (GLTA), one (1) Cockpit
 Indicator Unit Replacement (CIUR), and four to six (4-6) IR sensors. The Validated Online Life-Cycle Threat Report produced by DoW Intelligence and current USMC CONOPS continue to identify surface-to-
 air weapons as the most critical threat to assault operations. DoN LAIRCM capabilities enhance aircrew/aircraft survivability against advanced Man-Portable Air Defense Systems, Rocket Propelled Grenades,
 hostile gunfire, Anti-Aircraft Artillery, and laser-directed weapons. This budget supports procurement, Engineering Change Proposals (ECPs), integration, validation, Follow-On Test and Evaluation (FOT&E),$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                    Date: April 2026
